properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Accumulating snow to make travel difficult New Year's Eve into New Year's Day for much of New Brunswick. Snow will change briefly to rain over southern New Brunswick. Total snowfall: 10 to 25 cm. Locally higher amounts possible. Total rainfall: 2 to 10 mm. Locations: All of New Brunswick for snow, southern New Brunswick for rain. Time span: Tuesday morning into Wednesday morning, potentially persisting into Wednesday afternoon over northern New Brunswick. Remarks: A disturbance is expected to develop near Cape Cod early on New Year's Eve and track slowly northeastward across New Brunswick on New Year's Day. Snow is expected to develop Tuesday morning ahead of this system and spread to all of the province by late Tuesday afternoon. Snow will gradually change to possibly a brief period of freezing rain or ice pellets and then to rain over southern and eastern New Brunswick Tuesday night into Wednesday morning, but should persist as snow over northwestern sections well into Wednesday. The timing and combination of mixed precipitation could impact travel across much of the province on New Year's Eve or New Year's Day. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow and ice pellets changing to rain along with strong winds expected for New Year's Eve. Total snowfall: 2 cm over southwestern Nova Scotia to 10 cm in the north, possibly higher over the Cape Breton Highlands. Total rainfall: 5 to 20 mm. Maximum wind gusts: 70 to 80 km/h, likely higher in Les Suetes. Locations: All of Nova Scotia. Time span: Tuesday morning into Wednesday morning. Remarks: A disturbance is expected to develop near Cape Cod early on New Year's Eve and track slowly northeastward across New Brunswick on New Year's Day. Snow or rain is expected to develop Tuesday morning over southwestern Nova Scotia ahead of this system and then spread to all regions of the province by Tuesday evening. A period of ice pellets with a risk of freezing rain is now looking likely before the changeover to rain. Strong southeast winds gusting to 70 to possibly 80 km/h will develop Tuesday afternoon and evening then diminish overnight.
